summary: Meta: Why is Aziraphale so gay? - DictionaryWrites - Good Omens - Neil Gaiman & Terry Pratchett [Archive of Our Own]
title: Meta: Why is Aziraphale so gay? - DictionaryWrites - Good Omens - Neil Gaiman & Terry Pratchett [Archive of Our Own]
excerpt: An Archive of Our Own, a project of the Organization for Transformative Works
description:
So, there are three things people notice about Aziraphale when he meets them. Firstly, English. If I start talking about why Aziraphale chooses to come across as English, I’m going to start talking a lot about imperialism and cold indifference pretending to be polity and affability, and that’s a whole other essay, so let’s just move neatly on. Intelligent – yes, intelligent, that’s okay. And, then, “that he was gayer than a tree full of monkeys on nitrous oxide.” We know that Aziraphale isn’t actually gay, because the book tells us so: “angels are sexless unless they really want to make an effort.”[18]

But like…

People talk to Aziraphale, right, and it’s like there are big, blaring lights over his head that say, G A Y!! I AM GAY!! And what lights those lights? Because it isn’t as if he flirts with people – he’s charming in a weirdly reserved, librarian-esque way and polite. Part of it is in elements of his appearance. The tweed, the tartan, the wool and knit; the elegantly-manicured hands; the way he talks, politely and in a very well-read way that makes irritating Americans go, “Oh my god, I love English people,” and then list off some Scottish landmarks they know.

This meta is basically me picking apart the things that make Aziraphale come across as gayer than a tree full of monkeys on nitrous oxide, and then talking about why he’d choose to present himself like that, and also, that I love him. I love him so much.

Warnings for the canonically-used slurs, and a pinch of salt, esp re: the English and the Americans.

title: Meta: Why is Aziraphale so gay?
body:
read it on the AO3 at https://ift.tt/2TbprlN

by DictionaryWrites

I’ve been threatening for three days now to write out this meta about why Aziraphale chooses to present himself as gay, despite being sexless and not even a man, and here it is! It took eight straight hours of writing, and there are 35 footnotes, with constant reference to the text. Kill me!

This meta is basically me picking apart the things that make Aziraphale come across as gayer than a tree full of monkeys on nitrous oxide, and then talking about why he’d choose to present himself like that, and also, that I love him. I love him so much.

summary: So in the Spanish version of Good Omens, Crowley refers to Aziraphale as “angelito,” which, first of all, makes me lose my...
body:
So in the Spanish version of Good Omens, Crowley refers to Aziraphale as “angelito,” which, first of all, makes me lose my fucking mind, and second, he doesn’t just call him “ángel.” Like. He adds the “-ito,” which isn’t even necessary on Crowley’s part but makes it sound so much more tender. This makes Crowley calling Aziraphale an angel even more of a pet name.

Aziraphale refers to Crowley as “dear” and “dear boy” in the original, but in Spanish refers to him as “querido” and “querido amigo.” “Querido” by itself honestly sounds pretty gay to me, because I hear it casually used between like family members and lovers, but never between two casual male friends. As for “querido amigo,” I find that interesting because I don’t recall Aziraphale referring to Crowley as his friend in the English version, except for when the narrator mentions that being enemies for thousands of years makes them sort of friends. 

Anyway, it’s just interesting to see how translation can change some of the subtleties.

summary: Anathema gathered her things together and stepped out as haughtily as possible. She was quite sure neither of the two men had...
text:
Anathema gathered her things together and stepped out as haughtily as possible. She was quite sure neither of the two men had gone around to the back of the car, but the bike was unstrapped and leaning against the gate. There was definitely something very weird about them, she decided. Aziraphale bowed again. “So glad to have been of assistance,” he said.
“Thank you,” said Anathema, icily. “Can we get on?” said Crowley. “Goodnight, miss. Get in, angel.”
Ah. Well, that explained it. She had been perfectly safe after all.
source: GOOD OMENS Neil Gaiman and Terry Pratchett

summary:
Aziraphale held up the sword. There was a whoomph as it suddenly flamed like a bar of magnesium. 
“Once you’ve learned how to do...
text:
Aziraphale held up the sword. There was a whoomph as it suddenly flamed like a bar of magnesium.
“Once you’ve learned how to do it, you never forget,” he said.
He smiled at Crowley.
“I’d just like to say,” he said, “if we don’t get out of this, that … I’ll have known, deep down inside, that there was a spark of goodness in you.”
“That’s right,” said Crowley bitterly. “Make my day.” Aziraphale held out his hand. “Nice knowing you,” he said.
Crowley took it. “Here’s to the next time,” he said. “And … Aziraphale?”
“Yes.”
“Just remember I’ll have known that, deep down inside, you were just enough of a bastard to be worth liking.
source: GOOD OMENS Neil Gaiman and Terry Pratchett

summary: When Good Omens gets released I’m going to sit in front of my TV with a blanket over my head and a dangerous array of snackfoods...
body:
When Good Omens gets released I’m going to sit in front of my TV with a blanket over my head and a dangerous array of snackfoods and binge it all at once.

My stomach will regret it but my unending enthusiasm for this ridiculous work of fiction will not.
